a channel network effect in some respects.*

*BS:* That=E2=80=99s right. And the channel side, I think, is to your secon=
d point actually huge. The ability to =E2=80=94 because when you sell these=
 DOD programs, it=E2=80=99s not just, =E2=80=9CDo you have the right tool?=
=E2=80=9D, it=E2=80=99s do you have the security infrastructure and the pro=
gram management support and the ability to do all the Hill and lobbying pie=
ces and work with the Pentagon? Do they believe you can scale? Do you have =
a production system that can scale your hardware? All of these are very, ve=
ry hard and these are areas where I think when we=E2=80=99ve done these acq=
uisitions, we=E2=80=99ve been able to accelerate these companies on all of =
those fronts. How do we actually make these even more successful and enable=
 them to scale much bigger?

On the whole, the retention rate, just looking at some basic metrics of the=
se things, two, three years in, the retention of folks is like 5% turnover =
rate at a lot of these companies. It=E2=80=99s wild in terms of how much pe=
ople stay, see through the mission, I think that=E2=80=99s partly the natur=
e of defense. People get into it, it=E2=80=99s a passion, it=E2=80=99s a ca=
lling. Partly, I think the lesson I=E2=80=99ve learned with a lot of these =
acquisitions is you have to enable their dream to survive and thrive in the=
 new organization and then they=E2=80=99ll stay and they love it and everyo=
ne wins. So that=E2=80=99s really what we=E2=80=99ve tried to do is acceler=
ate them through the channels we basically have, pull them into these Latti=
ce systems, and enable them to be as successful as possible and it=E2=80=99=
s worked out incredibly well for us.

Recruiting, Diffusion, and Conduits

*You brought up three things that I wanted to ask about there, I=E2=80=99ll=
 start with that last one. This kind of goes back to 2017 and to go work fo=
r Anduril then was not a particularly popular thing to do, I can imagine th=
ere=E2=80=99s very strong selection effect in terms of the people that you =
got. It does feel like the vibe has changed a bit over the last few years. =
Number one, is that an accurate assessment? Number two, has that made life =
better because it=E2=80=99s easier to hire now, or has it made it in some r=
espects more difficult because you=E2=80=99re not getting that sort of sele=
ction effect of people who really believe and that=E2=80=99s why they=E2=80=
=99re going to go work for a company like Anduril?*

*BS:* Yeah, I think the vibe has changed dramatically, and I think Ukraine =
was the biggest motivator. I think before that, people really believed it w=
as even kind of crazy to talk about there might be a conflict with China, R=
ussia =E2=80=94 Putin=E2=80=99s still a bad person, people just thought you=
 were saber-rattling. The fact that there=E2=80=99s still bad people who wi=
ll use force to get their will is it=E2=80=99s been true for all of human h=
istory, and I don=E2=80=99t see any reason it=E2=80=99s going to stop now, =
and so the hard power deterrence matters, and I think people realize that a=
nd I think that was something that really shifted the popular perception of=
 these things.

From a recruiting perspective, my lesson on a lot of recruiting has been th=
e Silicon Valley crowd is hard, they typically want to work somewhere three=
 to five years, it=E2=80=99s very mercenary, they have no loyalty to the ar=
eas they are working, and it=E2=80=99s become hedonistic in a lot of weird =
ways, where you=E2=80=99re working for entertainment and not for the missio=
n and purpose of what you=E2=80=99re trying to do. Being in defense, I cert=
ainly think we see more people now showing up because it=E2=80=99s cool and=
 interesting, but mostly what we select for is people who have otherwise se=
lected into the defense world.

On software, that=E2=80=99s obviously a little less the case, you=E2=80=99r=
e really taking a lot of great talent from a lot of these areas. But I thin=
k when people get here, they see the impact of the problems, the challenge =
of it, how hard it is, how interesting it is and we=E2=80=99ve had an amazi=
ng time retaining people to date.

*Number two, to go back to your earlier, because that answer was super-inte=
resting, one thing that strikes me about this =E2=80=9CHow to sell into the=
 Pentagon and how you can scale these other startups very, very quickly=E2=
=80=9D =E2=80=94 it sounds like tech companies in general, I think where th=
e underrated effects of a very large platform like a Facebook or Google or =
an Apple buying a company is that that new innovation is diffused to billio=
ns of people basically overnight, when otherwise it would have taken fiftee=
n to twenty years, and it sounds like you=E2=80=99re the tech diffusion ope=
rator as far as getting stuff into the DOD. Do you think that sort of compa=
rison holds?*

*BS:* I think that=E2=80=99s something we want to get to. I think right now=
 that is more an aspiration at some point than I think kind of reality wher=
e it is today.

*Right. Because your biggest customer=E2=80=99s still more like Homeland Se=
curity and the experimental budgets. To get into the actual core DOD, is th=
at still sort of a bit of a lift?*

*BS:* We do a fair bit. So, counter-drone is probably one of the most matur=
e areas, and that=E2=80=99s an area where I think this sort of distribution=
 argument does hold pretty well, and I certainly think it will be true as w=
e start winning some of these bigger and bigger programs, which is like, =
=E2=80=9CHey, here=E2=80=99s an interesting capability. Okay, great. I can =
roll this out holistically now.=E2=80=9D So, I do think that will be true, =
and that is one of the beliefs here.

The challenge that the Defense Department also has is they have these small=
 companies with interesting ideas and the typical thing that=E2=80=99s happ=
ened is if they spend money with these guys, they will get swallowed up by =
the bigs or they go out of business because they couldn=E2=80=99t scale. It=
 kind of just goes in one of those two directions, it=E2=80=99s a pretty bi=
nary outcome and so it=E2=80=99s a real challenge. So it=E2=80=99s like how=
 do you get new performers?

*It sounds like consumer tech companies.*

*BS:* It=E2=80=99s very similar to consumer tech, and so it=E2=80=99s a rea=
l challenge for the buyer in this case to get access to these technologies,=
 and so the thing that=E2=80=99s always kind of flips on its head with DOD =
is it=E2=80=99s just, it=E2=80=99s this weird monopsony environment, they=
=E2=80=99re artificially creating markets. There=E2=80=99s a really fascina=
ting history, this is a quick aside, where when a lot of the modern system =
was set up under [Robert] McNamara ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_M=
cNamara ) of how the DOD does budgeting and planning and all these things, =
it was literally a belief that capitalism was going to fail and they needed=
 to adopt a socialist system of planning and central planning to enable the=
m to succeed, it=E2=80=99s completely wild. So there was actually a legacy =
of this more planned environment, it worked for quite a while. So this sort=
 of more capitalist environment is quite challenging for DOD to work in, it=
=E2=80=99s just not how their system is designed or incentivized today.

*On that point, one of the things about Robert Noyce ( https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Robert_Noyce ) , the founder of Intel, was he was very deliberate=
 about not getting sucked into government contracts for this reason. He=E2=
=80=99s like, =E2=80=9CIn the long run, the chip industry is going to depen=
d on scale. We are going to get scale via the consumer market and then that=
 will backfill into defense,=E2=80=9D which is exactly what happened. The b=
ig defense modernization in the =E2=80=9980s was all about saying, =E2=80=
=9CLook, the consumer market has these incredible chips. We have to figure =
out how to use them.=E2=80=9D*

*I=E2=80=99m curious, to what extent is this applicable to Anduril? I could=
 make the case that while the smartphone and the miniaturization and all th=
is stuff there has created a lot of the bits that make what we do possible.=
 On the other hand, you=E2=80=99re not making consumer products. Where do y=
ou fit in that tension there?*

*BS:* I think we=E2=80=99re the guys taking the microchips and making them =
into weapons and that=E2=80=99s our view has been that is exactly the corre=
ct thesis, that the innovation that is happening in the commercial world is=
 so fast.

*Right. So, you=E2=80=99re the conduit basically for creating that.*

*BS:* We=E2=80=99re the conduit, exactly. The challenge is there=E2=80=99s =
so many areas where this is true today, it=E2=80=99s like by the time you c=
an write a requirement and get a system built, you=E2=80=99re three generat=
ions of GPUs old. The DOD could spend any amount of money it wants on R&D f=
or machine learning models, and it will make exactly 0% difference to the p=
erformance of machine learning models in five years. It=E2=80=99s such a di=
fferent dynamic at this point where the DoD=E2=80=99s R&D budget back in th=
e =E2=80=9950s and =E2=80=9960s was a sizable percentage of GDP. It is a ma=
rginal percentage of GDP today and the amount of R&D that tech companies ar=
e putting in is so high and so you have all of this commercial innovation t=
hat is coming in incredibly cheap and incredibly effective because of the s=
cale effects, and then being able to tailor that to defense-unique applicat=
ions is really key.

The other thing I=E2=80=99ve seen is you have a natural bifurcation of most=
 of these companies where, back again, =E2=80=9960s, =E2=80=9970s, a lot of=
 companies had a DOD business. I read this interesting story about how ICBM=
s were created. General Motors was machining the inertial navigation parts,=
 RCA was making the navigation receivers, TWA was literally operating telem=
etry stations in The Bahamas for the tests off Cape Canaveral. It was just =
a very different time where you had a very different dynamic. When you look=
 at the dynamic today, the question is not, =E2=80=9CCan I make a better ma=
chine learning model?=E2=80=9D, the answer is, =E2=80=9CNo, I can=E2=80=99t=
=E2=80=9D. But can I build the unique data, train it for the right applicat=
ions, and deploy these into weapons systems faster than anyone else? Absolu=
tely. =E2=80=9CCan I adopt the latest gen of GPUs?=E2=80=9D

Another area we=E2=80=99re seeing huge return right now is the 5G community=
 invested so heavily in software-defined radios (SDR). When you look at how=
 the defense market worked prior to about three to five years ago, you had =
to custom tape-out chips, you had to make all these unique things, like it =
was a $100 million investment to get next-generation capabilities. Now, I j=
ust got to stay on the latest Xilinx and analog devices, SDRs, faster than =
anyone else, marry it up with GPUs and have the best software and packaging=
 for this, and I=E2=80=99ve got the most cutting-edge system at a very low =
dollar invested, comparatively.

And so, it=E2=80=99s just a very different time. Recognizing the fact that =
technology innovation is happening incredibly fast, whoever can apply it fa=
stest is going to have the advantage, is really where we=E2=80=99re at. The=
n, hopefully in the long run, we can also change the DOD procurement system=
s to recognize this fact as well, which is constant tech refresh, constant =
maturation, that=E2=80=99s the goal. We just want this, =E2=80=9CBuy the ne=
w iPhone every year, don=E2=80=99t lock in an iPhone from ten years ago =E2=
=80=94 like, what are you doing?=E2=80=9D. Figuring out that model is reall=
y the key for the future.

*Yeah, and to your point, it=E2=80=99s obviously a better way to do it, but=
 this is where having China as a way to change the old guard and change the=
 views was a really essential catalyst to make this possible.*

Production

*One more question from that earlier question. Where do you make products? =
You talked about scalability and the idea is you=E2=80=99re going to make a=
 consumable. You talked about the fact that China has massively more indust=
rial capacity. Obviously, you=E2=80=99re not making products in China. Wher=
e are they made and how much have you had to invest in building out this su=
pply chain capability?*

*BS:* The strategy we=E2=80=99ve taken is twofold. So, one is there=E2=80=
=99s a large amount of consumer and commercial manufacturing capacity withi=
n the US, so you can find a lot of companies that are making things for con=
sumer electronics and industrial electronics, and all these things. That do=
esn=E2=80=99t have to be defense-unique, there=E2=80=99s a lot of parts her=
e that could be farmed out to modern supply chain on this. So, we=E2=80=99v=
e been able to take advantage for piece part manufacturing, PCBA manufactur=
ing, composites, various things. Taking advantage of the industrial base th=
at does exist. We use COTS [commercial-off-the-shelf] parts whenever possib=
le. So, if we can just get a camera, let=E2=80=99s just buy a camera, why a=
re we making a custom camera if we don=E2=80=99t need to? We=E2=80=99ve bee=
n able to take advantage of the commercial industrial supply base in a very=
 big way.

The second though is then you get to the final assembly configuration and =
=E2=80=9CHow do I actually pull this together?=E2=80=9D A lot of the unique=
 parts we=E2=80=99re trying to drive into manufacturing are more around how=
 do we think about this as this sort of, we don=E2=80=99t need to spend a h=
uge amount to bring up a line. We can very quickly go from prototype into p=
roduction through kind of continuous process of maturing up work instructio=
n, supply chain, hardening each piece at a time as we continuously move thr=
ough this cycle, and that=E2=80=99s very hard. Getting that manufacturing s=
ystem working, so that you can do this fast introduction of prototypes, min=
imize your ramp time, and have constant change in iteration as you go, is a=
 very complicated process. So, we=E2=80=99ve invested heavily in that.

*Does that mean building your own assembly sites? Or are you trying to buil=
d an operating system across other ones?*

*BS:* Yeah.

*So you do have your own final assembly sites?*

*BS:* Yeah. We=E2=80=99ve got manufacturing in SoCal and Atlanta, and Massa=
chusetts. We=E2=80=99ve got manufacturing locations in a number of spots ri=
ght now and so our view is, =E2=80=9CHey, we=E2=80=99ll do full assembly te=
sts, manufacturing that=E2=80=99s high value, we can get a lot of lift out =
of doing this. But everything else we can pull out, let=E2=80=99s take adva=
ntage of the huge supply chain that already exists in the States.=E2=80=9D

*Yep, that makes sense.*

AI

*The last question, this is sort of an obvious one, is AI generally. I am c=
urious, you talked about China and Ukraine being big spurs for the Pentagon=
 changing their view. Palmer did say in an article a couple of weeks ago ( =
https://breakingdefense.com/2023/09/palmer-luckey-anduril-ipo-chatgpt-inter=
view/ ) that ChatGPT actually made selling a lot easier. Is that something =
that you=E2=80=99ve noticed as well, just a broad awareness of this? I mean=
 there=E2=80=99s obviously been tons of talk about AI ( https://www.nytimes=
.com/2023/09/13/technology/silicon-valley-ai-washington-schumer.html ) and =
the whole thing with China and chips and all that sort of thing in Washingt=
on, has there been a step change though over the last year that has made yo=
ur job easier in some respects?*

*BS:* The feeling of urgency and =E2=80=9CWe are running out of time to mak=
e a difference on the Taiwan scenario=E2=80=9D is palpable. It has changed =
dramatically in the last =E2=80=94 I think there=E2=80=99s a part of that, =
which is just time is running out. Xi is a little bit unstable, the bad fac=
ts on the economy in China don=E2=80=99t work in favor of this going well. =
So, I think there=E2=80=99s a little bit of that.

I do think the AI piece has kind of put a clearer marker on the competition=
 that exists between China and the US. First it was TikTok and then the AI =
piece, CHIPS Act was shortly after all that, and the AI pieces really has c=
rystallized for folks that we are in a unique time where long-term conseque=
ntial advantage will be established, and we need to secure that, but the st=
akes are high.

So, when the stakes are high, the desire for someone like Xi to mobilize ag=
ainst this becomes really consequential and so you end up in this very tric=
ky, precarious time where people believe tech is a huge advantage both from=
 a commercial and industrial base as well as defense base. Xi is getting mo=
re desperate, and this matters more than it ever has. That is a palpable fe=
eling in DC right now, people do not believe they=E2=80=99re in a slow race=
 here.

*AI is sort of a catch-all term, but I think one of the most interesting th=
ings about generative AI in particular is it=E2=80=99s really highlighted t=
he difference between probabilistic and deterministic computing. You go bac=
k to the way hardware platforms worked or you go back to your self-driving =
fifteen years ago, and it was pretty deterministic, like =E2=80=9CIf A, do =
B=E2=80=9D programming. Whereas AI, particularly in the generative perspect=
ive is probabilistic, and that=E2=80=99s why it can get stuff wrong, and it=
=E2=80=99s also why I can be more capable and creative in those things. How=
 does that apply, that dichotomy or that difference, if at all, to what you=
 are doing? Is it super important that you=E2=80=99re still pretty determin=
istic, or is this why it=E2=80=99s important to keep the human in the loop?=
 How much does that impact what you=E2=80=99re working on?*

*BS:* Predictability matters, but predictability is a bounded thing. When y=
ou employ a weapon, you want to know what it=E2=80=99s going to do, but you=
 want to know what it=E2=80=99s going to do within bounds. The DOD has alwa=
ys worked with a kind of stochastic lens to these things where with a weapo=
n, they talk about the error bounds =E2=80=94 how accurate is it going to b=
e, how it engages. They talk about with targeting, =E2=80=9CWhat=E2=80=99s =
the uncertainty around this?=E2=80=9D and so, they=E2=80=99ve always had th=
is notion of bounding the uncertainty on these things in very practical way=
s that you can train to an 18-year-old enlisted guy. It=E2=80=99s actually =
a pretty good system and so the reality is they=E2=80=99ve always dealt wit=
h uncertainty. When you deal with sensor systems, it is always statistical =
by nature, and so there=E2=80=99s always noise in your returns, so that has=
 always been the case.

When I think you start talking about autonomy systems making decisions now =
and the bounds become more fuzzy, you=E2=80=99ve got to reset those bounds,=
 and what I=E2=80=99m willing to let the systems do. The reality of how it=
=E2=80=99s going to shake out is it will just be bounded in a different way=
. We know that when I release this autonomous fighter jet, it=E2=80=99s goi=
ng to stay in this sort of box, doing these things, and it will engage acco=
rding to these rules that I have programmed. I think that will be true, and=
 to the extent that generative AI fits in those bounds, which it very much =
can, I can generate plans constrained within these inputs. I can use genera=
tive AI to evoke APIs that are inherently bounded, and so I think there=E2=
=80=99s a lot of applicability for thinking through things within limits an=
d how you activate the system in predictable ways and in transparent ways. =
That=E2=80=99s where I think these are going to get most readily applied.

The reality is most of the DOD=E2=80=99s job is descriptive, and so a lot o=
f the descriptive AI pieces have been much more beneficial, like computer v=
ision models, machine learning models, all these kind of classifiers. Very =
little of the DOD job is inherently creative. There=E2=80=99s some pieces a=
round the art of war and how you plan maneuvers and these different things =
where I do think there is a lot of applicability. But that implies to an ex=
tent you=E2=80=99ve been able to digitize and training it on context and un=
derstanding =E2=80=94 which historically has not been digitized.

So I think there=E2=80=99s just a mismatch there for now, but there=E2=80=
=99s still a ton of applicability on this on consuming information and inte=
lligence gathering, and capturing new materials. There=E2=80=99s all these =
great applications of it but from the, =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m going to find t=
he adversary and attack them,=E2=80=9D it=E2=80=99s the sort of thing that=
=E2=80=99s going to require a large degree of thoughtfulness, precision of =
how we proceed on that.

*Is there a Big Six now? Has Anduril graduated to that level? Or what is go=
ing to be necessary for you to get there and what might prevent you from be=
coming the Big Six as opposed to the Big Five?*

*BS:* The key for us is if we can get some of these major big strategic pla=
tforms adopted, employed, and rolled out, that is what=E2=80=99s going to m=
ove the needle the most. So if you=E2=80=99ve got the pedigree and the mass=
 to be able to produce, scale and deliver these next-generation capabilitie=
s and probably even more importantly, the DOD believes that it=E2=80=99s po=
ssible they know how to employ these, and they know what they want out of t=
hem. Where we=E2=80=99re kind of just going through the first generation of=
 this right now, they don=E2=80=99t even know how to fight with these right=
 now, and so the idea of how would you even use it is hard. If we get throu=
gh that, I think we will see this avalanche of new platforms wanting to go =
more autonomous, cheaper, all of that and that=E2=80=99s really when I thin=
k we=E2=80=99ll leapfrog into the top tier.

*And that=E2=80=99s when all the network effects of software and the disper=
sion advantage that you talked about would really come to bear?*

*BS:* You got it. That=E2=80=99s exactly the thesis.

*Very good. Well, Brian Schimpf, it was great talking to you and I look for=
ward to observing how Anduril evolves. And I hope we can talk again soon.*

